default1.2.
default&#xa0; 
defaultThe Department for Transport acknowledges that there are approximately 57,000 individuals working in the 
defaultNorth Sea
default, across 600 facilities. The only viable means of transferring workers in the 
defaultNorth Sea
default industry from shore to installation and from one installation to another is by helicopter. Three 
defaultUK
default helicopter companies operate approximately 100 aircraft in support of the exploitation of oil and gas around the 
defaultUK
default: Bristow Helicopters Ltd; Bond Offshore
default Helicopters Ltd; and CHC Scotia Ltd.  Main operating bases are: 
defaultAberdeen
default; Scatsta; 
defaultNorwich
default; North Denes; Humberside; and 
defaultBlackpool
default.  There are approximately 100 flights per day. 
default&#xa0;
default1.3.
default&#xa0; 
defaultOffshore helicopter operations represent a small section of 
defaultUK
default aviation. Ho
defaultwever, it provides critical support to the oil and gas industry, which is of significant economic importance. It is recognised by both industry and the CAA that these non-scheduled public transport operations take place in a hostile environment and are rel
defaultatively high risk. Therefore helicopter operations in the 
defaultNorth Sea
default are worthy of particular attention.  
